Formatting Text: Used to clean and standardize text data for better analysis
Why Format Text?
 Ensure consistency in spelling and structure.
 Make your data clean and ready for visuals or analysis.
 Fix common data entry issues like extra spaces, wrong case, inconsistent symbols.
To Format Text: Power Query Editor → Transform tab → Format dropdown
Text Formatting Options
1. UPPERCASE
 Converts all letters to CAPITALS.
 Good for standardizing codes, names, etc.
Example: "bangalore" → "BANGALORE"
2. lowercase
 Converts all letters to small case.
Example: "DATA SCIENCE" → "data science"
3. Capitalize Each Word
 Makes the first letter of each word uppercase, rest lowercase.
Example: "data analyst" → "Data Analyst"
Use Case: Formatting names, cities, titles.
4. Trim
 Removes extra spaces from the beginning and end of text.
Example: " John " → "John"
Use Case: Clean up manual entries or copied data.
5. Clean
 Removes non-printable characters (e.g., invisible symbols copied from web or PDFs).
Example: "Hello World" (with hidden character) → "Hello World"
6. Add Prefix / Add Suffix
 Adds text before (prefix) or after (suffix) each value.
Example – Add Prefix: Original: "123" → With prefix "ID-" → "ID-123"
Example – Add Suffix: Original: "Bangalore" → With suffix " City" → "Bangalore City"
Real-Life Use Cases:
Scenario
Formatting Used
Clean name column
Trim + Capitalize Each Word
Standardize product codes
UPPERCASE
Remove hidden web characters
Clean
Add tag before employee ID
Add Prefix ("EMP-")
Extracting Text: Used to pull out specific parts of text from a column
Why Use Text Extract?
 Extract useful parts from longer strings.
 Focus only on the needed portion of a value (e.g., first name from full name, domain from email).
 Helps in cleaning, splitting, and transforming data into usable formats.
To Access Extract: Transform tab → Extract (Dropdown)
Extract Options:
1. Extract First Characters
 Extracts the first N characters from the left.
Example: "Bangalore" → Extract first 3 → "Ban"
Use Case: Get area codes, year (from date string like "2024-05-21")
2. Extract Last Characters
 Extracts the last N characters from the right.
Example: "ABC12345" → Extract last 3 → "345"
Use Case: Get ID suffix, last digits of a code.
3. Extract Range
 Extracts characters starting from a position with a specific length.
Syntax: Start position (0-based) and Number of characters
Example: Text: "Karnataka" Start at 3, length 4 → "nata"
Use Case: Slice specific parts of fixed-format codes.
4. Text Before Delimiter
 Extracts everything before the specified character or symbol.
Example: "john.doe@gmail.com" Delimiter: @ → "john.doe"
Use Case: Get username from an email.
5. Text After Delimiter
 Extracts everything after the specified delimiter.
Example: "john.doe@gmail.com" Delimiter: @ → "gmail.com"
Use Case: Extract domain from email, location from a code.
6. Text Between Delimiters
 Extracts text between two specified delimiters.
Example: "Name[12345]Code" Start: [ , End: ] → "12345"
Use Case: Extract codes, tags, or IDs within brackets or quotes.
Number Based Operations:
What Are Statistical Operations?
Statistical operations help you analyze numeric data by summarizing and understanding patterns, trends, and variations. These are mostly used to:
 Get totals, averages, or counts
 Measure trends like min/max values
 Group data to identify patterns
To Access Statistics: Transform tab → Statistics dropdown (Only appears when you select a numeric column)
