General Advance Operations:
Button
What it Does
Typical Use Case
Mini Walk-Through & Result
Column From Examples(Add Column From Examples)
Learns a transformation from the examples you type.
“I need a new column that shows ‘Last, First’ names—but I don’t want to write any code.”
1. Select First Name & Last Name.
2. Column from Examples >From Selection.
3. In the new preview column, type “Smith, John”.
Power Query infers: Text.Combine({[LastName],[First Name]}, ", ") → Auto-builds the column for every row.
Custom Column
Lets you write an M formula of any complexity.
Calculations that the GUI can’t do directly (ratios, nested IFs, etc.).
Example: Profit= [Revenue] - [Cost]
Invoke Custom Function
Runs a user-defined function on each row, returning the result into a new column.
Re-use logic (e.g., distance between two lat/longs, an API call, a fiscal-year converter).
1. Create function fxFiscalYear(Date).
2. Add Column > Invoke Custom Function.
3. Pass [OrderDate] into the function. → New Fiscal Year column.
Conditional Column
Builds an IF…THEN…ELSE column without writing code.
Banding / labels (High, Medium, Low), pass/fail flags, text categorisation.
Configure:If [Sales] ≥ 1000 then "High"else if [Sales] ≥ 500 then "Medium"else "Low"
Index Column(From 0, From 1, or Custom)
Adds a running number.
Primary key substitute, order preservation, ranking, join helper.
Add Column >Index Column >From 1 → 1, 2, 3 …
Duplicate Column
Makes a copy of a column, leaving the original untouched.
Try a risky transformation without losing the original; set up splitting/formatting while preserving raw data.
Right-click ProductName > Duplicate Column. Rename copy to ProductName_Clean and apply transformations only to the duplicate.
AI INSIGHTS:
Group allows you to apply pre-trained AI models and Azure ML services directly to your data in Power Query, enabling powerful transformations without coding.
1. Text Analytics
Use Case: Apply natural language processing (NLP) models to textual data.
Features:
 Detect Language – Identify the language of the text.
In order to detect the language or sentiment of the text will go with analytics
 Extract Key Phrases – Pull important keywords or phrases from a sentence.
 Sentiment Analysis – Return positive/neutral/negative score for text.
Note: Not available in query editor without sign in
2. Vision
Use Case: Apply image analysis models (via Azure Cognitive Services).
Features:
 Detect objects in image URLs
 Identify content type (e.g., landscape, text, object)
 Get descriptions and tags
Example Table:
Image URL
https://.../cat.jpg
After applying Image Tagging:
Image URL
Tags
.../cat.jpg
cat, animal, pet
3. Azure Machine Learning
Use Case: Apply custom ML models deployed in your Azure Machine Learning workspace.
How it works:
 You need an Azure ML account
 Models must be deployed as web services
 Power Query can connect and pass data to your model to get predictions
What is Data Modelling in Power BI?
Data modelling is the process of connecting different tables using relationships and optimizing your data structure to enable powerful analysis with DAX and visuals.
Key Components of Data Modelling
1. Tables
 Imported from various sources (Excel, SQL, APIs, etc.)
 Can be fact (transactions) or dimension (lookup).
Fact Table:
 Stores transactional data
 Contains foreign keys that relate to dimension tables
 Grows over time (new rows keep adding)
 Includes measures (like SUM, AVERAGE, COUNT, etc.)
Dimension Table:
 Contains unique values (primary key)
 Used to filter, group, and slice data in visuals
 Typically small in size
2. Relationships
 Connect tables using common columns (keys)
 Types:
o One-to-many (most common)
o Many-to-one
o Many-to-many (rare & needs careful handling)
3. Primary & Foreign Keys
 Used to relate two tables:
o Customer ID in Customer Table (primary key)
o Customer ID in Sales Table (foreign key)
4. Star Schema vs Snowflake Schema
 Star Schema: Fact table in center, connected to dimensions
 Snowflake Schema: Dimensions are normalized (sub-tables linked to dimension tables)
Important Tools in Power BI for Modelling
Feature
Use
Manage Relationships
View/edit relationships between tables
Model View
Drag-drop to create/manage relationships visually
Mark as Date Table
Designate a calendar table for time intelligence
Hide Columns
Hide technical columns from report view
Create Calculated Columns/Measures
Add logic using DAX
Role-Level Security (RLS)
Restrict data visibility based on user roles
Best Practices
1. Use surrogate keys (like ID numbers) instead of names for relationships.
2. Avoid bi-directional relationships unless necessary.
3. Keep your model as flat (star-schema) as possible.
4. Always create a Calendar Table for time-based analysis.
5. Use measures over calculated columns for efficiency.
Example
Tables:
 Sales (Fact Table): Sale ID, Customer ID, Product ID, Date, Quantity, Revenue
 Customers (Dim Table): Customer ID, Name, Region
 Products (Dim Table): Product ID, Name, Category
 Calendar (Dim Table): Date, Month, Year
Relationships:
 Sales[Customer ID] → Customers[Customer ID]
 Sales[Product ID] → Products[Product ID]
 Sales[Date] → Calendar[Date]
